## Frequently Asked Questions

### Does it matter which charger I buy for my specific car?

Not really, no. Every EV sold in the UK uses the standard Type 2 connector, so any home charger will work with any car. The differences that matter are the charger's smart features (tariff integration, solar support, app quality) rather than car compatibility.

### My car has an 11kW onboard charger — do I need an 11kW home charger?

No. On a standard UK single-phase electricity supply, the maximum charging speed is 7.4kW regardless of your car's onboard charger capacity. You'd need three-phase power to charge above 7.4kW at home. The 11kW onboard charger is useful at public AC charging points and three-phase home setups. See our [3-phase guide](/best-picks/best-3-phase-ev-charger-uk/).

### Should I use my car's built-in charging schedule or my charger's?

Either works, but using the charger's schedule (especially with Ohme and Intelligent Octopus Go) is generally better. The charger can optimise across variable electricity prices in ways most cars' built-in schedulers can't. Using both simultaneously can sometimes cause conflicts — pick one and stick with it.

### Can I charge two different EVs from the same charger?

Yes, any Type 2 charger works with any Type 2 car. If you have two EVs and one charger, you simply unplug one and plug in the other. If you want to charge both simultaneously, you'll need two chargers — the Easee's load balancing makes this particularly cost-effective.

### Are manufacturer-branded chargers better for my specific car?

No. They're typically rebadged versions of existing chargers (BMW sells a rebranded Wallbox, for example) with a dealer markup. You'll get equal or better value buying directly from charger brands like Ohme, myenergi, or Wallbox and using an independent OZEV-registered installer.

